('SAT', 'Which quotation from Wives and Daughters most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Wives and Daughters is an 1866 novel by Elizabeth Gaskell. In the novel, two young women named Molly and Cynthia attend a charity ball. Gaskell''s narrator, in depicting these characters, acknowledges a historical distance between the reader and the characters themselves:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“So it was, for this was to be a very good ball, people said; and a large party from the Towers was coming, and a duchess in diamonds among the number.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"B","text":"“Molly, too, though not so good a dancer as Cynthia, was becoming engaged pretty deeply; and, it must be confessed, she was longing to dance every dance, no matter with whom.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"C","text":"“When Molly and Cynthia were young—before railroads were, and before their consequences, the excursion-trains which take every one up to London now-a-days—to go to an annual charity-ball was a very allowable and favourite piece of dissipation.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Gaskell''s narrator emphasizes how much daily life has changed between the characters'' era and the reader''s present."},{"id":"D","text":"“Molly felt innocent enough, so she offered no justification of herself, and made no reply; indeed she was more occupied in watching Cynthia, who seemed changed in a way she could not understand.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The claim states: Gaskell''s narrator emphasizes how much daily life has changed between the characters'' era and the reader''s present.

