('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Mill on the Floss most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Mill on the Floss is an 1860 novel by George Eliot. The narrator describes Maggie Tulliver, a clever girl whose eagerness to learn is rarely encouraged by those around her:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“Maggie''s hair, as she threw off her bonnet, tumbled down in a heavy mass that was the despair of her mother and the amusement of her brother Tom.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"B","text":"“The afternoon was already advanced, and the mill kept up its steady, low thunder while the cart-horses plodded back from the fields.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"C","text":"“Tom, you see, was not given to reflection: he was a boy who knew exactly what he wanted, and was determined to get it by the shortest road.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"D","text":"“She was a creature full of eager, passionate longings for all that was beautiful and glad; thirsty for all knowledge; with an ear straining after dreamy music that died away and would not come near to her—and yet the people who lived close to her took no note of it.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator stresses that Maggie''s intelligence goes largely unrecognized by the adults in her life."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'The claim states: The narrator stresses that Maggie''s intelligence goes largely unrecognized by the adults in her life.

