('SAT', 'Which quotation from The House of Mirth most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The House of Mirth is a 1905 novel by Edith Wharton. The narrator observes Lily Bart, a young woman acutely conscious of how others perceive her:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“It was a long time since she had visited the country, and the green stillness of the place soothed her after the noise of the town.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"B","text":"“The afternoon was perfect, and a tepid air, laden with the scent of the gardens, drifted in at the open windows of the train.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"C","text":"“She was so evidently the victim of the civilization which had produced her, that the links of her bracelet seemed like manacles chaining her to her fate.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator emphasizes that Lily is keenly aware of being judged by appearances."},{"id":"D","text":"“Selden paused in surprise; in the afternoon rush of the Grand Central Station his eyes had been refreshed by the sight of Miss Lily Bart.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The claim states: The narrator emphasizes that Lily is keenly aware of being judged by appearances.

