('SAT', 'Which quotation from Walden most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Walden is an 1854 work by Henry David Thoreau, written during his stay in a cabin by Walden Pond. Thoreau explains his reasons for living apart from town:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“I had three chairs in my house; one for solitude, two for friendship, three for society, and the visitors took them as they would.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"B","text":"“The pond was my well ready dug, and for four months in the year its water was as cold as it was pure at all times.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“In the morning I bathed my intellect in the stupendous and cosmogonal philosophy, beside which our modern world and its literature seem puny.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"D","text":"“I went to the woods because I wished to live deliberately, to front only the essential facts of life, and see if I could not learn what it had to teach, and not, when I came to die.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Thoreau presents his retreat to the woods as a deliberate experiment in living simply and intentionally."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'The claim states: Thoreau presents his retreat to the woods as a deliberate experiment in living simply and intentionally.

