('SAT', 'Which quotation from Middlemarch most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Middlemarch is an 1872 novel by George Eliot. The narrator reflects on Dorothea Brooke, whose large ideals find little outlet in the life available to her:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“Her full nature, like that river of which Cyrus broke the strength, spent itself in channels which had no great name on the earth.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator suggests that Dorothea''s capacity for great feeling is wasted on a life that offers it no scope."},{"id":"B","text":"“Miss Brooke had that kind of beauty which seems to be thrown into relief by poor dress, and her hand and wrist were so finely formed.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“The town of Middlemarch, in the years just preceding the Reform, was at that time spirited with the discussion of every new arrival.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"D","text":"“Mr. Casaubon''s home was called Lowick, and the house had an air of autumnal decline even at the height of summer.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The claim states: The narrator suggests that Dorothea''s capacity for great feeling is wasted on a life that offers it no scope.

