('SAT', 'Which quotation from Looking Backward most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Looking Backward is an 1888 novel by Edward Bellamy in which a narrator wakes in a future society. Here the narrator reflects on how the people of that future regard the inequalities of his own century:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“My hostess, observing my fatigue, suggested that the remainder of my questions might be reserved until I had rested from the strangeness of the day.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"B","text":"“They cannot understand how, with such means of comfort and happiness at command, the men of my century could have gone on living in the way they did.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator reports that the future society views his era''s inequality as a source of bewilderment rather than admiration."},{"id":"C","text":"“I had been, when awake, a man of about thirty, in sound health, and in the enjoyment of an income more than sufficient for my wants.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"D","text":"“The city stretched out before me, its avenues lined with trees and broken at intervals by open squares filled with fountains and statuary.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The claim states: The narrator reports that the future society views his era''s inequality as a source of bewilderment rather than admiration.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', false),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Country of the Pointed Firs most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Country of the Pointed Firs is an 1896 work by Sarah Orne Jewett. The narrator, a summer visitor to a coastal village, describes her landlady Mrs. Todd, an herb-gatherer whose knowledge impresses her:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“The road went up and down, and the small gray house stood close upon it, with a footpath leading round to the side door.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"B","text":"“I had arrived in the early summer, and the days were long and bright, with a coolness in the air that came up from the water at evening.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"C","text":"“Mrs. Todd would be gone the greater part of an afternoon, and return with her basket full and her face flushed with the heat of the day.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"D","text":"“She was an ardent lover of herbs, both wild and tame, and the sea-breezes blew into the low end-window of the house laden with not only sweet-brier and sweet-mary.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator presents Mrs. Todd''s knowledge of plants as a kind of inherited wisdom rather than mere habit."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'The claim states: The narrator presents Mrs. Todd''s knowledge of plants as a kind of inherited wisdom rather than mere habit.

