('SAT', 'Which quotation from Self-Reliance most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Self-Reliance is an 1841 essay by Ralph Waldo Emerson. In it, Emerson urges his readers to trust their own judgment over the settled opinions of society:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“There is a time in every man''s education when he arrives at the conviction that envy is ignorance and that imitation is suicide.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"B","text":"“I read the other day some verses written by an eminent painter which were original and not conventional, and the soul always hears an admonition in such lines.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“A foolish consistency is the hobgoblin of little minds, adored by little statesmen and philosophers and divines.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"D","text":"“Society everywhere is in conspiracy against the manhood of every one of its members; the virtue in most request is conformity.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Emerson argues that conforming to public opinion costs a person their independence of mind."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'The claim states: Emerson argues that conforming to public opinion costs a person their independence of mind.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', false),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from The House of Mirth most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The House of Mirth is a 1905 novel by Edith Wharton. The narrator observes Lily Bart, a young woman acutely conscious of how others perceive her:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“She was so evidently the victim of the civilization which had produced her, that the links of her bracelet seemed like manacles chaining her to her fate.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator emphasizes that Lily is keenly aware of being judged by appearances."},{"id":"B","text":"“Selden paused in surprise; in the afternoon rush of the Grand Central Station his eyes had been refreshed by the sight of Miss Lily Bart.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“The afternoon was perfect, and a tepid air, laden with the scent of the gardens, drifted in at the open windows of the train.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"D","text":"“It was a long time since she had visited the country, and the green stillness of the place soothed her after the noise of the town.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The claim states: The narrator emphasizes that Lily is keenly aware of being judged by appearances.

