('SAT', 'Which quotation from Self-Reliance most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Self-Reliance is an 1841 essay by Ralph Waldo Emerson. In it, Emerson urges his readers to trust their own judgment over the settled opinions of society:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“There is a time in every man''s education when he arrives at the conviction that envy is ignorance and that imitation is suicide.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"B","text":"“A foolish consistency is the hobgoblin of little minds, adored by little statesmen and philosophers and divines.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"C","text":"“I read the other day some verses written by an eminent painter which were original and not conventional, and the soul always hears an admonition in such lines.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"D","text":"“Society everywhere is in conspiracy against the manhood of every one of its members; the virtue in most request is conformity; self-reliance is its aversion, for it loves not realities and creators, but names and customs.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Emerson argues that conforming to public opinion costs a person their independence of mind."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'The claim states: Emerson argues that conforming to public opinion costs a person their independence of mind.

