('SAT', 'Which quotation from Walden most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Walden is an 1854 work by Henry David Thoreau, written during his stay in a cabin by Walden Pond. Thoreau explains his reasons for living apart from town:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“In the morning I bathed my intellect in the stupendous and cosmogonal philosophy, beside which our modern world and its literature seem puny.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"B","text":"“The pond was my well ready dug, and for four months in the year its water was as cold as it was pure at all times.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“I went to the woods because I wished to live deliberately, to front only the essential facts of life, and see if I could not learn what it had to teach, and not, when I came to die, discover that I had not lived.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Thoreau presents his retreat to the woods as a deliberate experiment in living simply and intentionally."},{"id":"D","text":"“I had three chairs in my house; one for solitude, two for friendship, three for society, and the visitors took them as they would.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The claim states: Thoreau presents his retreat to the woods as a deliberate experiment in living simply and intentionally.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from Middlemarch most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Middlemarch is an 1872 novel by George Eliot. The narrator reflects on Dorothea Brooke, whose large ideals find little outlet in the life available to her:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“Her full nature, like that river of which Cyrus broke the strength, spent itself in channels which had no great name on the earth; but the effect of her being on those around her was incalculably diffusive, for the growing good of the world is partly dependent on unhistoric acts.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator suggests that Dorothea''s capacity for great feeling is wasted on a life that offers it no scope."},{"id":"B","text":"“Miss Brooke had that kind of beauty which seems to be thrown into relief by poor dress, and her hand and wrist were so finely formed.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“The town of Middlemarch, in the years just preceding the Reform, was at that time spirited with the discussion of every new arrival.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"D","text":"“Mr. Casaubon''s home was called Lowick, and the house had an air of autumnal decline even at the height of summer.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The claim states: The narrator suggests that Dorothea''s capacity for great feeling is wasted on a life that offers it no scope.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from Civil Disobedience most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Civil Disobedience is an 1849 essay by Henry David Thoreau. Thoreau argues that a citizen''s conscience should take precedence over the demands of an unjust government:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“I have traveled a good deal in Concord, and everywhere the inhabitants seemed to me to be doing penance in a thousand remarkable ways.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"B","text":"“The night in prison was novel and interesting enough, and I saw the town through a quite new and singular set of windows.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"C","text":"“It is not desirable to cultivate a respect for the law, so much as for the right; the only obligation which I have a right to assume is to do at any time what I think right, and law never made men a whit more just.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Thoreau contends that individuals must not surrender their moral judgment to the authority of the state."},{"id":"D","text":"“I have paid no poll-tax for six years, and I was put into a jail once on this account, for one night.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The claim states: Thoreau contends that individuals must not surrender their moral judgment to the authority of the state.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from Wives and Daughters most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Wives and Daughters is an 1866 novel by Elizabeth Gaskell. In the novel, two young women named Molly and Cynthia attend a charity ball. Gaskell''s narrator, in depicting these characters, acknowledges a historical distance between the reader and the characters themselves:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“When Molly and Cynthia were young—before railroads were, and before their consequences, the excursion-trains which take every one up to London now-a-days—to go to an annual charity-ball was a very allowable and favourite piece of dissipation.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Gaskell''s narrator emphasizes how much daily life has changed between the characters'' era and the reader''s present."},{"id":"B","text":"“So it was, for this was to be a very good ball, people said; and a large party from the Towers was coming, and a duchess in diamonds among the number.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“Molly, too, though not so good a dancer as Cynthia, was becoming engaged pretty deeply; and, it must be confessed, she was longing to dance every dance, no matter with whom.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"D","text":"“Molly felt innocent enough, so she offered no justification of herself, and made no reply; indeed she was more occupied in watching Cynthia, who seemed changed in a way she could not understand.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The claim states: Gaskell''s narrator emphasizes how much daily life has changed between the characters'' era and the reader''s present.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Influence of Rationalism most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Influence of Rationalism is an 1883 essay by George Eliot (the pen name of Marian Evans). In this essay, Eliot describes the “general reader” as an individual who does not have specialized literary or scholarly training; she then asserts that some talented writers, rather than shunning a “general” readership, publish with this specific audience in mind:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“The vagueness and vacillation of popular books are not devices of timidity; they are the honest result of the writer''s own mental character, faithfully transcribed.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"B","text":"“In fact, the general reader likes sound views—nothing extreme, but something between the excesses of the past and the excesses of the present; this modern reader may be known by the cordiality with which he assents to indistinct, blurred statements.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Eliot characterizes the general reader as preferring ideas that are familiar and moderate rather than original or demanding."},{"id":"C","text":"“These characteristics of the general reader render him incapable of assimilating ideas unless they are administered in a highly diluted form, drop by careful drop.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"D","text":"“There is a valuable class of books on great subjects which have something of the character and functions of good popular lecturing; they are not original, not subtle, not of close logical texture.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The claim states: Eliot characterizes the general reader as preferring ideas that are familiar and moderate rather than original or demanding.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Mill on the Floss most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Mill on the Floss is an 1860 novel by George Eliot. The narrator describes Maggie Tulliver, a clever girl whose eagerness to learn is rarely encouraged by those around her:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“Tom, you see, was not given to reflection: he was a boy who knew exactly what he wanted, and was determined to get it by the shortest road.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"B","text":"“The afternoon was already advanced, and the mill kept up its steady, low thunder while the cart-horses plodded back from the fields.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"C","text":"“She was a creature full of eager, passionate longings for all that was beautiful and glad; thirsty for all knowledge; with an ear straining after dreamy music that died away and would not come near to her—and yet the people who lived close to her took no note of it.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator stresses that Maggie''s intelligence goes largely unrecognized by the adults in her life."},{"id":"D","text":"“Maggie''s hair, as she threw off her bonnet, tumbled down in a heavy mass that was the despair of her mother and the amusement of her brother Tom.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The claim states: The narrator stresses that Maggie''s intelligence goes largely unrecognized by the adults in her life.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from Cranford most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Cranford is an 1853 work by Elizabeth Gaskell depicting a small English town. The narrator gently mocks the way the town''s genteel ladies disguise their economy as elegant principle:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“The Cranford ladies had only an occasional little quarrel, carried on in a few peppery words and angry jerks of the head, just enough to prevent the even tenor of their lives from becoming too flat.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"B","text":"“I had often noticed the efficiency and even the comfort of her small establishment, where everything had its proper place and its proper hour.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"C","text":"“We none of us spoke of money, because that subject savoured of commerce and trade, and though some might be poor, we were all aristocratic; we had tacitly agreed to ignore that any with whom we associated on terms of equality could ever be prevented by poverty from anything they wished to do.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator suggests that the townswomen reframe their lack of money as a matter of refined taste."},{"id":"D","text":"“Miss Jenkyns wore a cravat, and a little bonnet like a jockey-cap, and altogether had the appearance of a strong-minded woman.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The claim states: The narrator suggests that the townswomen reframe their lack of money as a matter of refined taste.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from Looking Backward most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Looking Backward is an 1888 novel by Edward Bellamy in which a narrator wakes in a future society. Here the narrator reflects on how the people of that future regard the inequalities of his own century:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“The city stretched out before me, its avenues lined with trees and broken at intervals by open squares filled with fountains and statuary.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"B","text":"“They cannot understand how, with such means of comfort and happiness at command, the men of my century could have gone on living in the way they did; to them our arrangements seem not wicked merely, but, what is harder to forgive, supremely foolish.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator reports that the future society views his era''s inequality as a source of bewilderment rather than admiration."},{"id":"C","text":"“My hostess, observing my fatigue, suggested that the remainder of my questions might be reserved until I had rested from the strangeness of the day.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"D","text":"“I had been, when awake, a man of about thirty, in sound health, and in the enjoyment of an income more than sufficient for my wants.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The claim states: The narrator reports that the future society views his era''s inequality as a source of bewilderment rather than admiration.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true);

INSERT INTO public.questions (exam_type, question_text, stimulus_text, stimulus_type, question_type, options, correct_answer, explanation, topic, subtopic, section, difficulty, is_platform_question, ai_generated, source, source_metadata, domain_id, skill_id, challenge_only) VALUES
('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Country of the Pointed Firs most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Country of the Pointed Firs is an 1896 work by Sarah Orne Jewett. The narrator, a summer visitor to a coastal village, describes her landlady Mrs. Todd, an herb-gatherer whose knowledge impresses her:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“Mrs. Todd would be gone the greater part of an afternoon, and return with her basket full and her face flushed with the heat of the day.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"B","text":"“She was an ardent lover of herbs, both wild and tame, and the sea-breezes blew into the low end-window of the house laden with not only sweet-brier and sweet-mary, but balm and sage and borage and mint, wormwood and southernwood, as if she had gathered the learning of generations into that one fragrant room.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator presents Mrs. Todd''s knowledge of plants as a kind of inherited wisdom rather than mere habit."},{"id":"C","text":"“I had arrived in the early summer, and the days were long and bright, with a coolness in the air that came up from the water at evening.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"D","text":"“The road went up and down, and the small gray house stood close upon it, with a footpath leading round to the side door.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The claim states: The narrator presents Mrs. Todd''s knowledge of plants as a kind of inherited wisdom rather than mere habit.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Awakening most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Awakening is an 1899 novel by Kate Chopin. The narrator describes a moment when Edna Pontellier begins to recognize a new sense of selfhood:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“The water of the Gulf stretched out before her, gleaming with the million lights of the sun, and a quiet breeze came up from the south.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"B","text":"“The children were gathered upon the porch, and their laughter rose and fell as the afternoon wore on toward its close.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"C","text":"“In short, Mrs. Pontellier was beginning to realize her position in the universe as a human being, and to recognize her relations as an individual to the world within and about her—a ponderous weight of wisdom to descend upon the soul of a young woman of twenty-eight.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator marks this moment as the beginning of Edna''s awareness of herself as a distinct individual."},{"id":"D","text":"“Mr. Pontellier wore eye-glasses, and he had a way of turning them upon his wife as one might examine a piece of personal property.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The claim states: The narrator marks this moment as the beginning of Edna''s awareness of herself as a distinct individual.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from Self-Reliance most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Self-Reliance is an 1841 essay by Ralph Waldo Emerson. In it, Emerson urges his readers to trust their own judgment over the settled opinions of society:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“Society everywhere is in conspiracy against the manhood of every one of its members; the virtue in most request is conformity; self-reliance is its aversion, for it loves not realities and creators, but names and customs.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Emerson argues that conforming to public opinion costs a person their independence of mind."},{"id":"B","text":"“There is a time in every man''s education when he arrives at the conviction that envy is ignorance and that imitation is suicide.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"C","text":"“I read the other day some verses written by an eminent painter which were original and not conventional, and the soul always hears an admonition in such lines.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"D","text":"“A foolish consistency is the hobgoblin of little minds, adored by little statesmen and philosophers and divines.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The claim states: Emerson argues that conforming to public opinion costs a person their independence of mind.

