('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Influence of Rationalism most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Influence of Rationalism is an 1883 essay by George Eliot (the pen name of Marian Evans). In this essay, Eliot describes the “general reader” as an individual who does not have specialized literary or scholarly training; she then asserts that some talented writers, rather than shunning a “general” readership, publish with this specific audience in mind:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“In fact, the general reader likes sound views—nothing extreme, but something between the excesses of the past and the excesses of the present; this modern reader may be known by the cordiality with which he assents to indistinct, blurred statements.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Eliot characterizes the general reader as preferring ideas that are familiar and moderate rather than original or demanding."},{"id":"B","text":"“There is a valuable class of books on great subjects which have something of the character and functions of good popular lecturing; they are not original, not subtle, not of close logical texture.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“These characteristics of the general reader render him incapable of assimilating ideas unless they are administered in a highly diluted form, drop by careful drop.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"D","text":"“The vagueness and vacillation of popular books are not devices of timidity; they are the honest result of the writer''s own mental character, faithfully transcribed.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The claim states: Eliot characterizes the general reader as preferring ideas that are familiar and moderate rather than original or demanding.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Mill on the Floss most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Mill on the Floss is an 1860 novel by George Eliot. The narrator describes Maggie Tulliver, a clever girl whose eagerness to learn is rarely encouraged by those around her:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“Maggie''s hair, as she threw off her bonnet, tumbled down in a heavy mass that was the despair of her mother and the amusement of her brother Tom.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"B","text":"“She was a creature full of eager, passionate longings for all that was beautiful and glad; thirsty for all knowledge; with an ear straining after dreamy music that died away and would not come near to her—and yet the people who lived close to her took no note of it.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator stresses that Maggie''s intelligence goes largely unrecognized by the adults in her life."},{"id":"C","text":"“Tom, you see, was not given to reflection: he was a boy who knew exactly what he wanted, and was determined to get it by the shortest road.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"D","text":"“The afternoon was already advanced, and the mill kept up its steady, low thunder while the cart-horses plodded back from the fields.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The claim states: The narrator stresses that Maggie''s intelligence goes largely unrecognized by the adults in her life.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from Cranford most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Cranford is an 1853 work by Elizabeth Gaskell depicting a small English town. The narrator gently mocks the way the town''s genteel ladies disguise their economy as elegant principle:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“The Cranford ladies had only an occasional little quarrel, carried on in a few peppery words and angry jerks of the head, just enough to prevent the even tenor of their lives from becoming too flat.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"B","text":"“Miss Jenkyns wore a cravat, and a little bonnet like a jockey-cap, and altogether had the appearance of a strong-minded woman.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"C","text":"“We none of us spoke of money, because that subject savoured of commerce and trade, and though some might be poor, we were all aristocratic; we had tacitly agreed to ignore that any with whom we associated on terms of equality could ever be prevented by poverty from anything they wished to do.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator suggests that the townswomen reframe their lack of money as a matter of refined taste."},{"id":"D","text":"“I had often noticed the efficiency and even the comfort of her small establishment, where everything had its proper place and its proper hour.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The claim states: The narrator suggests that the townswomen reframe their lack of money as a matter of refined taste.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from Looking Backward most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Looking Backward is an 1888 novel by Edward Bellamy in which a narrator wakes in a future society. Here the narrator reflects on how the people of that future regard the inequalities of his own century:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“My hostess, observing my fatigue, suggested that the remainder of my questions might be reserved until I had rested from the strangeness of the day.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"B","text":"“The city stretched out before me, its avenues lined with trees and broken at intervals by open squares filled with fountains and statuary.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“I had been, when awake, a man of about thirty, in sound health, and in the enjoyment of an income more than sufficient for my wants.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"D","text":"“They cannot understand how, with such means of comfort and happiness at command, the men of my century could have gone on living in the way they did; to them our arrangements seem not wicked merely, but, what is harder to forgive, supremely foolish.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator reports that the future society views his era''s inequality as a source of bewilderment rather than admiration."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'The claim states: The narrator reports that the future society views his era''s inequality as a source of bewilderment rather than admiration.

