('SAT', 'Which quotation from Middlemarch most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Middlemarch is an 1872 novel by George Eliot. The narrator reflects on Dorothea Brooke, whose large ideals find little outlet in the life available to her:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“The town of Middlemarch, in the years just preceding the Reform, was at that time spirited with the discussion of every new arrival.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"B","text":"“Miss Brooke had that kind of beauty which seems to be thrown into relief by poor dress, and her hand and wrist were so finely formed.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“Her full nature, like that river of which Cyrus broke the strength, spent itself in channels which had no great name on the earth; but the effect of her being on those around her was incalculably diffusive, for the growing good of the world is partly dependent on unhistoric acts.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator suggests that Dorothea''s capacity for great feeling is wasted on a life that offers it no scope."},{"id":"D","text":"“Mr. Casaubon''s home was called Lowick, and the house had an air of autumnal decline even at the height of summer.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The claim states: The narrator suggests that Dorothea''s capacity for great feeling is wasted on a life that offers it no scope.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from Civil Disobedience most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Civil Disobedience is an 1849 essay by Henry David Thoreau. Thoreau argues that a citizen''s conscience should take precedence over the demands of an unjust government:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“I have traveled a good deal in Concord, and everywhere the inhabitants seemed to me to be doing penance in a thousand remarkable ways.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"B","text":"“I have paid no poll-tax for six years, and I was put into a jail once on this account, for one night.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“The night in prison was novel and interesting enough, and I saw the town through a quite new and singular set of windows.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"D","text":"“It is not desirable to cultivate a respect for the law, so much as for the right; the only obligation which I have a right to assume is to do at any time what I think right, and law never made men a whit more just.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Thoreau contends that individuals must not surrender their moral judgment to the authority of the state."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'The claim states: Thoreau contends that individuals must not surrender their moral judgment to the authority of the state.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from Wives and Daughters most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Wives and Daughters is an 1866 novel by Elizabeth Gaskell. In the novel, two young women named Molly and Cynthia attend a charity ball. Gaskell''s narrator, in depicting these characters, acknowledges a historical distance between the reader and the characters themselves:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“So it was, for this was to be a very good ball, people said; and a large party from the Towers was coming, and a duchess in diamonds among the number.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"B","text":"“Molly, too, though not so good a dancer as Cynthia, was becoming engaged pretty deeply; and, it must be confessed, she was longing to dance every dance, no matter with whom.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"C","text":"“Molly felt innocent enough, so she offered no justification of herself, and made no reply; indeed she was more occupied in watching Cynthia, who seemed changed in a way she could not understand.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"D","text":"“When Molly and Cynthia were young—before railroads were, and before their consequences, the excursion-trains which take every one up to London now-a-days—to go to an annual charity-ball was a very allowable and favourite piece of dissipation.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Gaskell''s narrator emphasizes how much daily life has changed between the characters'' era and the reader''s present."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'The claim states: Gaskell''s narrator emphasizes how much daily life has changed between the characters'' era and the reader''s present.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Influence of Rationalism most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Influence of Rationalism is an 1883 essay by George Eliot (the pen name of Marian Evans). In this essay, Eliot describes the “general reader” as an individual who does not have specialized literary or scholarly training; she then asserts that some talented writers, rather than shunning a “general” readership, publish with this specific audience in mind:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“There is a valuable class of books on great subjects which have something of the character and functions of good popular lecturing; they are not original, not subtle, not of close logical texture.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"B","text":"“These characteristics of the general reader render him incapable of assimilating ideas unless they are administered in a highly diluted form, drop by careful drop.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"C","text":"“In fact, the general reader likes sound views—nothing extreme, but something between the excesses of the past and the excesses of the present; this modern reader may be known by the cordiality with which he assents to indistinct, blurred statements.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Eliot characterizes the general reader as preferring ideas that are familiar and moderate rather than original or demanding."},{"id":"D","text":"“The vagueness and vacillation of popular books are not devices of timidity; they are the honest result of the writer''s own mental character, faithfully transcribed.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'The claim states: Eliot characterizes the general reader as preferring ideas that are familiar and moderate rather than original or demanding.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Mill on the Floss most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Mill on the Floss is an 1860 novel by George Eliot. The narrator describes Maggie Tulliver, a clever girl whose eagerness to learn is rarely encouraged by those around her:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“Tom, you see, was not given to reflection: he was a boy who knew exactly what he wanted, and was determined to get it by the shortest road.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"B","text":"“The afternoon was already advanced, and the mill kept up its steady, low thunder while the cart-horses plodded back from the fields.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"C","text":"“Maggie''s hair, as she threw off her bonnet, tumbled down in a heavy mass that was the despair of her mother and the amusement of her brother Tom.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"D","text":"“She was a creature full of eager, passionate longings for all that was beautiful and glad; thirsty for all knowledge; with an ear straining after dreamy music that died away and would not come near to her—and yet the people who lived close to her took no note of it.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator stresses that Maggie''s intelligence goes largely unrecognized by the adults in her life."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'The claim states: The narrator stresses that Maggie''s intelligence goes largely unrecognized by the adults in her life.

