('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Country of the Pointed Firs most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Country of the Pointed Firs is an 1896 work by Sarah Orne Jewett. The narrator, a summer visitor to a coastal village, describes her landlady Mrs. Todd, an herb-gatherer whose knowledge impresses her:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“She was an ardent lover of herbs, both wild and tame, and the sea-breezes blew into the low end-window of the house laden with not only sweet-brier and sweet-mary, but balm and sage and borage and mint, wormwood and southernwood, as if she had gathered the learning of generations into that one fragrant room.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator presents Mrs. Todd''s knowledge of plants as a kind of inherited wisdom rather than mere habit."},{"id":"B","text":"“The road went up and down, and the small gray house stood close upon it, with a footpath leading round to the side door.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“Mrs. Todd would be gone the greater part of an afternoon, and return with her basket full and her face flushed with the heat of the day.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"D","text":"“I had arrived in the early summer, and the days were long and bright, with a coolness in the air that came up from the water at evening.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The claim states: The narrator presents Mrs. Todd''s knowledge of plants as a kind of inherited wisdom rather than mere habit.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Awakening most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Awakening is an 1899 novel by Kate Chopin. The narrator describes a moment when Edna Pontellier begins to recognize a new sense of selfhood:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“Mr. Pontellier wore eye-glasses, and he had a way of turning them upon his wife as one might examine a piece of personal property.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"B","text":"“In short, Mrs. Pontellier was beginning to realize her position in the universe as a human being, and to recognize her relations as an individual to the world within and about her—a ponderous weight of wisdom to descend upon the soul of a young woman of twenty-eight.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator marks this moment as the beginning of Edna''s awareness of herself as a distinct individual."},{"id":"C","text":"“The children were gathered upon the porch, and their laughter rose and fell as the afternoon wore on toward its close.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"D","text":"“The water of the Gulf stretched out before her, gleaming with the million lights of the sun, and a quiet breeze came up from the south.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The claim states: The narrator marks this moment as the beginning of Edna''s awareness of herself as a distinct individual.

