('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Country of the Pointed Firs most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Country of the Pointed Firs is an 1896 work by Sarah Orne Jewett. The narrator, a summer visitor to a coastal village, describes her landlady Mrs. Todd, an herb-gatherer whose knowledge impresses her:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“She was an ardent lover of herbs, both wild and tame, and the sea-breezes blew into the low end-window of the house laden with not only sweet-brier and sweet-mary, but balm and sage and borage and mint, wormwood and southernwood, as if she had gathered the learning of generations into that one fragrant room.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator presents Mrs. Todd''s knowledge of plants as a kind of inherited wisdom rather than mere habit."},{"id":"B","text":"“The road went up and down, and the small gray house stood close upon it, with a footpath leading round to the side door.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“I had arrived in the early summer, and the days were long and bright, with a coolness in the air that came up from the water at evening.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"D","text":"“Mrs. Todd would be gone the greater part of an afternoon, and return with her basket full and her face flushed with the heat of the day.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'The claim states: The narrator presents Mrs. Todd''s knowledge of plants as a kind of inherited wisdom rather than mere habit.

