('SAT', 'Which quotation from The Awakening most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'The Awakening is an 1899 novel by Kate Chopin. The narrator describes a moment when Edna Pontellier begins to recognize a new sense of selfhood:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“The water of the Gulf stretched out before her, gleaming with the million lights of the sun, and a quiet breeze came up from the south.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"B","text":"“In short, Mrs. Pontellier was beginning to realize her position in the universe as a human being, and to recognize her relations as an individual to the world within and about her—a ponderous weight of wisdom to descend upon the soul of a young woman of twenty-eight.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: The narrator marks this moment as the beginning of Edna''s awareness of herself as a distinct individual."},{"id":"C","text":"“The children were gathered upon the porch, and their laughter rose and fell as the afternoon wore on toward its close.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"D","text":"“Mr. Pontellier wore eye-glasses, and he had a way of turning them upon his wife as one might examine a piece of personal property.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The claim states: The narrator marks this moment as the beginning of Edna''s awareness of herself as a distinct individual.

