('SAT', 'Which quotation from Self-Reliance most effectively illustrates the claim?', 'Self-Reliance is an 1841 essay by Ralph Waldo Emerson. In it, Emerson urges his readers to trust their own judgment over the settled opinions of society:', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"“A foolish consistency is the hobgoblin of little minds, adored by little statesmen and philosophers and divines.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (related but insufficient). It touches the same passage yet illustrates a weaker or different point than the claim asserts."},{"id":"B","text":"“I read the other day some verses written by an eminent painter which were original and not conventional, and the soul always hears an admonition in such lines.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (off the claim). It reports a concrete detail from the same scene but never states the idea the claim makes."},{"id":"C","text":"“There is a time in every man''s education when he arrives at the conviction that envy is ignorance and that imitation is suicide.”","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (different point). It describes a character or moment in the passage that addresses a separate idea, not this claim."},{"id":"D","text":"“Society everywhere is in conspiracy against the manhood of every one of its members; the virtue in most request is conformity; self-reliance is its aversion, for it loves not realities and creators, but names and customs.”","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. This quotation puts the claim into words: Emerson argues that conforming to public opinion costs a person their independence of mind."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'The claim states: Emerson argues that conforming to public opinion costs a person their independence of mind.

The correct quotation is the one that puts that idea into words. The other three quote accurate but unrelated lines from the same work — scene-setting, description, or character detail that does not bear on the claim.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"literary_quotation","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
('SAT', 'Which finding, if true, would most directly support Dr. Lee''s hypothesis?', 'Dr. Lee grew bean seedlings under controlled conditions that differed only in daily light. Based on this work, Dr. Lee hypothesized that greater daily light tends to produce higher stem height.', 'passage', 'multiple_choice', '[{"id":"A","text":"Stem height rose where daily light was greater, though those groups also differed in a second, unmeasured way.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (confounded). If a second variable also differs, the result cannot be pinned on daily light."},{"id":"B","text":"Among groups matched on every other condition, those with more daily light showed more stem height at each level — leaving no rival explanation for the difference.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct. Because the groups differ only in daily light, the rise in stem height can be tied to daily light as the hypothesis requires."},{"id":"C","text":"Raising daily light was shown to cause stem height to climb, since the two increased together.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (cause vs. correlation). Rising together shows association, not proven causation."},{"id":"D","text":"At the single highest level of daily light, stem height reached its maximum value.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"Incorrect (too narrow). One data point is not the relationship across the groups."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Step 1 — Identify the hypothesis: greater daily light leads to higher stem height.

Step 2 — A finding supports it only if it reports that direct, varied relationship. The correct choice does. Each distractor fails differently — it reverses the result, names an unrelated measure, credits a confound, claims cause from mere co-variation, or never varies daily light.', 'Information and Ideas', 'Command of Evidence', 'reading_writing', 'hard', true, true, 'scholaris_ai', '{"rw_subtype":"textual_evidence","rw_format":"hypothesis_support","generator":"generate-coe-fresh.mjs","coe_fresh_v1":true,"dsat_blueprint_v1":true,"length_tiered":true}'::jsonb, 'information', 'COE', true),
